Guidelines for Alcester Community Library City Hours:

*please stay away if you feel ill
*call in requests are welcome and the librarian will have your books ready for pick up
*use of a mask is Highly recommended when in the library
*Beginning September First during City library hours from 5:00-7:00 T, W, Th MASKS WILL BE MANDATORY
*please use hand sanitizer before entering the library
*please limit your visit to 30 minutes or less
*only 10 patrons in the library at a time
*children under 12 should be accompanied by an adult
*please practice social distancing (at least 6 feet apart)
*please use the book drop when returning books
*computer use will be available

City Librarian will:

*follow the city guidelines
*wear a mask when others are present
*sanitize door handles, counter surfaces, and other high touch areas every hour
*books will be quarantined for at least 3-4 days

post_text:
The Alcester Community Library will be beginning summer hours on 06/09/2020. There will be some restrictions in place to keep our community safe and healthy.
*Stay away if you are feeling ill.
*Call in requests are welcome and books can be picked up during business hours.
*Use of a mask is RECOMMENDED while in the library (Provided by Patrons).
*Use hand sanitizer when entering (Provided by Library).
*Please limit your visits to 30 minutes or less.
*Only 10 patrons in the library at a time.
*Children under 12 should be accompanied by an adult.
*Please stay 6 feet apart.
*Chairs with cloth upholstery will be unavailable, metal chairs in place for cleaning purposes.
*Use book drops for all book returns.
*Maker Space Items will not be available until a cleaning system is designed.
*Computer use will be limited, or will not be available until a cleaning system is designed.

LIBRARIAN WILL
*Wear a mask while in the presence of patrons.
*Sanitize books.
*Sanitize door handles, counter and other high traffic areas every hour.

May 20 at 5:52 PM ·

[The Christmas Barn] Pre-order from the Farm Store

SPECIAL AUTHOR SIGNED & LIMITED NUMBERED EDITION

This special edition book, The Christmas Barn, is signed by both author and illustrator Jennifer and John Churchman AND includes a specially designed and numbered, limited edition bookplate and holiday card created by the Author/Illustrator team, John and Jennifer Churchman.
https://www.sweetpeafriendsbookstore.com/
The book can also be personalized if you wish and will be shipped on Publication Date of September 15, 2020. Single, 2PK, 5PK available. Free Shipping

A warm new Christmas story from the creators of the New York Times Bestselling Children's Book The SheepOver!

When the Old Pine Tree cracks and falls after an autumn storm, Farmer John knows just what to do. He will give the farm animals a very special present for Christmas. He draws up a plan, and piece by piece, a structure is built, while the farm animals--sheep, dogs, chickens, geese, ducks, and some alpacas--look on in wonder at what their Christmas gift will be!

post_text: Princess In Black fans, your favorite character is on the case of the Coronavirus! 😃 Click on the link to download the mini story for the mini book-lover in your life!
shared_text:
Candlewick Press
May 1 at 1:44 PM ·

✨ Twinkle twinkle little SMASH! ✨ The creators of the New York Times-bestselling Princess in Black series—Shannon Hale, Dean Hale, and LeUyen Pham—have created a child-friendly public service announcement about the Coronavirus. Download The Princess in Black and the Case of the Coronavirus now! https://bit.ly/2y7CLzk
‍
In the words of the creators:
“LeUyen, Dean and I are all parents self-isolating at home with our children. The anxiety and distancing is hard enough on our older kids, but we know that younger kids might be having an even harder time. We hoped that it’d help if a familiar book friend like the Princess in Black talked them through it. Even the Princess in Black is staying home! Even Princess Sneezewort had to cancel playdates! LeUyen had the idea of creating a short comic to download and share widely so caregivers could have an extra tool for talking to kids. Our goal is both to help kids understand what’s going on and to help them feel less alone.”

post_text: Want to come along as this librarian experiences Harry Potter for the first time? Follow our school library Instagram page @books4cubs for daily updates and other shenanigans. Check out the first HP book on Libby in ebook or audio!
shared_text:
Nola Conner
April 7 at 12:44 AM · Instagram ·

Librarian confession: I’ve never read Harry Potter. (Don’t blame my friends. They tried to convince me!) But I decided there’s no time like the present. The ebook is available and I have the time. I’m reading a chapter a day and you get to witness it. First time or 100th time—read with me and tell me what you think! Check out our library page (https://alcesterhudsonlibrary.weebly.com/) for great free ways to read online! #schoollibrary #schoollibrarian #harrypotter #harrypotternewbie #books4cubs #whatyoucandowithalibrarycard

post_text: Dearest Friends, Keep Smiling, we will get through this. We are hearty South Dakotans. I would like to reiterate Superintendent/Elementary principal, Mr. Tim Rheid...."Read to your young child or have your young child read to you." That being said, please take full advantage of the Overdrive capabilities. These downloadable books are free and easily accessible. All you need is a device that uses the internet, your library number, and the easily followed directions I posted on March 21. If you need your library number, please email me at alcestercitylibrary@gmail.com. I would love to assist you.

We wish you could come visit us for our spring book fair, but this is a season of doing things differently! If you have run out of reading materials at home, consider shopping our online book fair from Scholastic. They have selections for all grades and orders get shipped directly to homes! The online fair is available March 30-April 12. Let us know if you have any questions!

(For some reason, some devices are not able to click through the link. If this is the case for you, go to scholastic.com/fair and search Alcester-Hudson)

post_text:
We have a new face in the library! Stop by and introduce yourself to our new public librarian, Michele Norling, as she gets settled and learns the ropes in the library. Michele is married to a farmer and they live on an acreage near Centerville that has been in the family for 100+ years. She has two adult children, two young grandchildren, two dogs, and several barn cats. Hobbies include reading, sewing, baking, and collecting Willow Tree figurines and church cookbooks!
Welcome, Michele!

post_text: What an amazing book fair week! Look at all the books we were able to bring to our school! (So many that it was hard to fit them all in the picture!!) Thank you to all who participated in our classroom and community coin wars. With nearly $1300 in coin war donations, we were able to spend over $300 on fulfilling classroom wish lists, (not including the many donations that were made to classroom libraries throughout book fair week by individuals!) We were also able to buy everything we wanted off the book fair for our library collection! THANK YOU!

post_text: Sixth graders and eighth graders spent the afternoon at the library trying out some Lego Robotics. Lauren Hollenbeck from the Union County Extension Service provided 4 boxes, each with a robot to put together. Each group got their Robot together and running. Great Job!!

post_text:
LEGO OPEN UP
The Alcester Public Library is starting a LEGO program called Open Up. OPEN UP your imagination, OPEN UP new sets of LEGO bricks, and OPEN UP a fun way to spend time at your library. This program will be for children in 3rd-6th grades. Our first event will be a FAMILY event on Wednesday, March 4th, at the library from 6-7 pm. We will play LEGO games, open up new sets of LEGO bricks, and share some food. After that we will meet at the library on Wednesday afternoons from 3:30-4:30 pm and have a time to build and create4 with the LEGO sets that the library has purchased. Come and be part of a new event happening at your Alcester Public Library

It's book fair week at the elementary school! The sixth graders helped us decorate, their teachers helped us promote the book fair with a joust during Monday morning opening, and today we have a lot of grandparents coming to visit! If you aren't able to come but would like to support the elementary library by buying at the fair, you can buy online until September 20th. Books will be shipped to the elementary school for free when the online fair has ended!
Link to the online store at http://bookfairs.scholastic.com/bookfairs/cptoolkit/homepage.do?method=homepage&url=alcesterhudsonelemschool
and click on the SHOP NOW button in the middle of the page.

post_text: The library will be closed another time this summer for our last project. We are putting new laminate on our check out desk and we will need to be closed from Aug. 5th to Aug. 12th so we can get this last project done. Be sure to stop in and pick up lots of books to make it through the week. Call 934-2601 if you have any questions. Most of the books are out on the shelves, as Jackie and I have been working all week on this project.

post_text: Join us for the summer book discussion on Wed. Aug. 13th at 7:00 at the library. We are using the book Dakota: a Spiritual Geography by Kathleen Norris. This is the "One Book South Dakota" and is sponsored by the South Dakota Humanities Council. We will have Marilyn Carlson Aronson as a guest discussion leader. We have the books here at the library so you just need to stop and pick up a copy or call us at 934-2601.
